2072.subject: SBS
2072.descrlong: Covers U.S. societies, government, and territorial and economic expansion from pre-contact Native America to 1920. Starts students on a teaching pathway addressing how they might teach this content, and prepares students for a major concentration in history. Emphasizes research and analysis of primary sources consistent with California State standards for teaching fifth and eighth grade U.S. history. Central issues in this course are class, ethnicity, gender, and multiculturalism.

2132.subject: SBS
2132.descrlong: Introduces students to college-level reading, writing, speaking, and listening skills through an exploration of and student responses to written and visual source materials covering the history of the US from pre-contact Native America to 1920. Further develops reading skills through a focus on divergent perspectives. Central themes this course focuses on include race relations, class, ethnicity, and gender. (Offered Spring semester.)

2164.subject: SBS
2164.descrlong: Examines US history through multiple and diverse perspectives.   Introduces students to college-level reading and writing through an exploration of and student responses to written and visual source materials covering the history of the US from pre-contact Native America to 1877.
